b"Happy Pride from Zoom! Last week, we paired with photographer Justin Wee (@djdumpling) and friends to celebrate the LGBTQIA+ community in the Pushing Forward On Zoom photo series, culminating with a day-long program of art, food, discussion, & tons of fun. 

The event raised donations for G.L.I.T.S. and the Trans Justice Funding Project, and we're happy to announce that, with Zoom's donation matching, the total raised was $42k! 

Even as Pride Month comes to a close, stay loud and proud, friends!"

b'The final subject of our \xe2\x80\x9cPushing Forward on Zoom\xe2\x80\x9d Pride portrait series is Charlene Carruthers (@CharleneCarruthers). A political strategist, writer, and leading community organizer in today\xe2\x80\x99s movement for Black liberation, Charlene is the founder of the Chicago Center for Leadership and Transformation, and author of Unapologetic: A Black, Queer and Feminist Mandate for Radical Movements. \nCharlene shares with us, \xe2\x80\x9cThis is a moment where connecting with the people I love and care about, the people I work with, the people I am in movement with is perhaps more important than it\xe2\x80\x99s ever been, and so we use every tool at our disposal to be able to connect to one another and to connect to as many people as possible. I\xe2\x80\x99ve used Zoom particularly to reach thousands of people across the world.\xe2\x80\x9d Charlene, thank you\xe2\x80\x94we\xe2\x80\x99re endlessly grateful for the work you do to shape the world into a better place! (photo: @djdumpling)'

b'The fourth subject of our \xe2\x80\x9cPushing Forward on Zoom\xe2\x80\x9d Pride portrait series is Peyton Dix (@PeytonDix). Peyton is the Special Projects Editor at InStyle, and the former Head of Social at PAPER. She specializes in audience and engagement growth. Her work is rooted in digital storytelling and amplifying Black, Queer, and femme voices.\n\nAbout her time using Zoom, Peyton shares, "I think right now we\xe2\x80\x99re seeing the value of communication and how so many things can be lost in translation. I think what\xe2\x80\x99s wonderful about Zoom is the reinforcing of seeing someone\xe2\x80\x99s face while you\xe2\x80\x99re having conversation, specifically conversations that are difficult but you should be having. Personally I\xe2\x80\x99ve used it as a platform to communicate with co-workers individually and group settings, and clearly right now we have to have a lot of conversations in our workplace about race, representation, and so I only hope this isn\xe2\x80\x99t the end of that and only a continuation of more conversations that are uncomfortable but productive." We celebrate you for your work and your words, Peyton! (photo: @djdumpling)'

b'The third subject of our \xe2\x80\x9cPushing Forward on Zoom\xe2\x80\x9d Pride portrait series is Angel Nafis (@anaffy). Angel is the author of the poetry collection BlackGirl Mansion. She is a Cave Canem fellow, the recipient of a Millay Colony residency, an Urban Word NYC mentor, and the founder and curator of the Greenlight Bookstore Poetry Salon. In 2011 she represented NYC at both the Women of the World Poetry Slam and the National Poetry Slam. In 2016, Angel was a recipient of the Ruth Lilly and Dorothy Sargent Rosenberg Poetry Fellowship from the Poetry Foundation and in 2017 she was awarded a Creative Writing fellowship from the National Endowment for the Arts. Facilitating writing workshops and reading poems globally, she lives in Brooklyn.

About her time using Zoom, Angel shares, \xe2\x80\x9cAs we were forced into isolation, I have been thinking about how I can continue to be in service of my communities as a poet and a teacher. Zoom has allowed us a new way of finding togetherness, which has been crucial to the way we move through this moment.\xe2\x80\x9d
Thank you for your words, your art, and all you do, Angel! (photo: @djdumpling)'

b"Though the current state of the world hasn\xe2\x80\x99t been very celebratory, June is Pride month. So, to celebrate Pride while also giving back to the community, we teamed up with photographer Justin Wee (@djdumpling) to create 'Pushing Forward on Zoom,' a fundraiser show (on June 25th) and photo series focused on the LGBTQIA+ community. All money raised through this fundraiser will be donated to the Trans Justice Funding Project and G.L.I.T.S., and Zoom will be matching donations up to $50,000. RSVP now at zoom.us/pushingforward - link also in bio!"

b'We love when great people are connected with great opportunities. Watch as this year\xe2\x80\x99s @toryburchfoundation Fellows receive the surprise acceptance announcement on Zoom from @toryburch herself. Congratulations, #ToryBurchFellows!'

b"We've loved seeing all the unique, creative and heartwarming ways you are staying connected on Zoom\xe2\x80\x94from board meetings to birthdays to barre classes, and everything in between. \nWe've created a place to celebrate all the amazing things happening on Zoom. Check out OnZoom.com and share your #OnZoom story."
b'Happy Father\xe2\x80\x99s Day, from our Zoom dads to you!'

b'Continuing our \xe2\x80\x9cPushing Forward on Zoom\xe2\x80\x9d Pride series, our second LGBTQIA+ portrait subject is chef and artist DeVonn Francis (@tuna__turner). DeVonn is the mastermind behind Yardy World, a one-of-a-kind hospitality company exploring the role of food and art in Caribbean culture.\n\nAs a first-generation Jamaican-American, DeVonn says, \xe2\x80\x9cZoom has been really helpful in fostering community for my company, and my own vision and mission as a chef, because we\xe2\x80\x99re not just bringing food to people, but we\xe2\x80\x99re also finding ways to teach people how to take care of themselves and invest in their health and wellness from a distance.\xe2\x80\x9d Thank you for connecting people and for changing the way that we think about how Black and Queer narratives are centered in the food world, DeVonn. We\xe2\x80\x99re grateful for all you do! (photo: @djdumpling)'

b"Though the current state of the world hasn\xe2\x80\x99t been very celebratory, June is Pride month. So, to celebrate Pride while also giving back to the community, we teamed up with photographer Justin J Wee (@djdumpling) to create 'Pushing Forward on Zoom,' a fundraiser show (on June 25th) and photo series focused on the LGBTQIA+ community. The series represents how queer people are using this moment to physically occupy space and visibilize themselves over Zoom in a moment where convening in real life is harder. All money raised through this fundraiser will be donated to the Trans Justice Funding Project and G.L.I.T.S., and Zoom will be matching donations up to $50,000. \nTo kick off the series, our first \xe2\x80\x9cPushing Forward\xe2\x80\x9d subject is Peppermint (@peppermint247). A longtime key figure in queer nightlife, Peppermint is a trailblazing actress, singer, DJ, reality star, and activist, who\xe2\x80\x99s defying limitations. She uses Zoom to perform, plan, and connect with her community.\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0Peppermint is particularly concerned about the challenges faced by transgender and non-binary people in today\xe2\x80\x99s political climate, and she takes every available opportunity to speak on the issue. Peppermint is currently recording her fifth studio album, and she looks forward to breaking new ground and being a positive voice during troublesome times. \nWe\xe2\x80\x99re so lucky to have her as a guest host and performer for our Pushing Forward fundraiser on June 25th. Thank you for all you do, Peppermint!"
